AGI -&nbsp;
<span> The Indian yoga guru Baba Ramdev, both popular and controversial, is in the viewpoint of the Supreme Court along with his company based on traditional care systems of the Asian country for promising miraculous and discredited Western medicine. </span
Accused of outrage for publishing advertisements in which he claimed that his Ayurdic medicines could cure diseases such as cancer and coronavirus, in contrast to court orders, Ramdev's apologies were rejected Wednesday by the Indian court.
&nbsp;
"We do not accept them, we reject them," said Judge Hima Kohli, in the remarks from the Indian Express newspaper, about the affidadavit in which the founder of Patanjali apologized.
&nbsp;
"Their apologies do not convince the Court. We think it's more than apology in words," Judge Kohli said at the time. Ram Kisan Yadav, known as Baba Ramdev, is on the bank of the defendants after the Indian Medical Association filed a complaint for Patanjali's attacks on Western medicine by the press.
&nbsp;
Ramdev questioned during a television seminar in 2021 the drug used against coronavirus and said that thousands of people died after consuming medicines against this disease, and his company has published in the past press announcements promising to cure numerous diseases with traditional remedies.
In fact, the yoga guru even marketed a product for the treatment of covid-19, which presented at an event attended by the then Indian Health Minister, Harsh Vardhan.
&nbsp;
After being criticized by the Supreme Court, last November Ramdev committed himself not to criticize Western medicine and not to promise more miraculous cures.
However, the announcements continued, prompting the maximum Indian judicial authority to initiate proceedings for outrage at the court, whose next hearing will be held on 16 April.&nbsp;

